==English==
===Etymology===
From '''[[integer]]'''

===Adjective===
'''integral''' (''no [[comparative]] or [[superlative]]'')

#[[constitute|Constituting]] a [[whole]] together with other [[part]]s or [[factor]]s; not [[omittable]] or [[removable]]
#{{mathematics}} Of or relating to an [[integer]].

====Synonyms====
*(''constituting a whole''): [[immanent]], [[inherent]], [[necessary]]

====Translations====
*Finnish: [[oleellinen]] (oleellinen osa) (1)
*German: [[integral#German|integral]] (1)

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
'''integral''' (''plural'' '''integrals''')
#{{analysis}} A numerical [[measure]] computed by a [[limit]]ing process in which the [[domain]] of a [[function]] is divided into small [[subinterval]]s and the value of the function at a point in each subinterval is multiplied by the measurement of that subinterval, all these products then being summed.<!--encyclopedic: It is often denoted by its symbol '''ʃ''' which is similar in appearance to an elongated "S".-->

====Synonyms====
*(''in analysis''): [[antiderivative]]

====Derived terms====
*[[integral calculus]]
*[[Riemann integral]]
*[[Riemann-Stieltjes integral]]
*[[Lebesque integral]]

====Related terms====
*[[integer]]
*[[integration]]
*[[integrity]]

